{
  "texts": [
    "If the latter is not accounted for, the estimated amplitude of microlensing from the data will be biased.",
    "For that reason, one can alternatively derive the amplitude of microlensing directly from the data, as explained in Sect. 3.2.1 and Sect.",
    "The requirement to compare pairs of lensed images implies that the interpretation of the microlensing signal is in general ambiguous: either one image is magnified or the other one is demagnified.",
    "It can also be that microlensing is taking place simultaneously in both images in a pair.",
    "The comparison of multiple pairs of images in quads helps resolving this ambiguity."
  ]
}